{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658641"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20785"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20785"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.83,0.09,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13660"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78719"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12633"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA child presents with paroxysmal cough ending with an inspiratory \u0027whoop\u0027 sound. Laboratory findings show a marked peripheral lymphocytosis of 85%. Pathological examination reveals bronchial mucosal erosion, hyperemia, and mucopurulent exudate. The lung alveoli remain open and intact. There is hypercellularity and enlargement of mucosal lymph follicles and peribronchial lymph nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measles virus","Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Bordetella pertussis","Streptococcus pyogenes","Epstein-Barr virus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is classic for pertussis (whooping cough), which is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003EBordetella pertussis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EParoxysmal cough ending with an inspiratory \u0027whoop\u0027\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMarked peripheral lymphocytosis (up to 90%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBronchial mucosal erosion, hyperemia, and mucopurulent exudate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHypercellularity and enlargement of mucosal lymph follicles and peribronchial lymph nodes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELung alveoli remaining open and intact (unless superinfected)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes infectious mononucleosis with features of sore throat, lymphadenopathy, and fatigue. While it can cause lymphocytosis, it does not typically cause the respiratory pathology described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles virus\u003C/strong\u003E causes a systemic infection with characteristic maculopapular rash, Koplik spots, and can lead to pneumonia, but does not cause the paroxysmal cough with whooping or the specific bronchial pathology described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorynebacterium diphtheriae\u003C/strong\u003E causes diphtheria, characterized by a pseudomembranous pharyngitis with a grey adherent membrane. It does not typically cause significant lymphocytosis or the bronchial pathology described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pharyngitis and scarlet fever but does not cause the paroxysmal cough with whooping or the marked lymphocytosis described. Streptococcal respiratory infections typically present with fever, exudative pharyngitis, and neutrophilia rather than lymphocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pertussis (whooping cough) is caused by Bordetella pertussis and features laryngotracheobronchitis with bronchial mucosal erosion, hyperemia, and mucopurulent exudate.","A striking peripheral lymphocytosis (up to 90%) is characteristic of pertussis infection.","Pertussis causes hypercellularity and enlargement of mucosal lymph follicles and peribronchial lymph nodes, while lung alveoli typically remain open and intact unless superinfected."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 365."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78719"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20785"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78719"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T13:57:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T13:58:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13660"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95979"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","